{"id":"project-LICHEN-u0ui","title":"Missing validation of callback return value in nodedb_peer_snapshot","description":"File: lichen/subsys/lichen/meshtastic/adapter.c:1124-1129

  state->peer_count = adapter->ops.get_peers(
      state->peers, ARRAY_SIZE(state->peers), adapter->ops.user_data);
  if (state->peer_count > ARRAY_SIZE(state->peers)) {
      state->peer_count = ARRAY_SIZE(state->peers);
  }

The callback get_peers is passed peer_cap as the maximum number of peers to write. The return value is then clamped if it exceeds the array size.

However, this check happens AFTER the callback has already executed. A misbehaving callback could write beyond state->peers bounds before returning an out-of-range count.

The callback contract states it should respect peer_cap, but defensive programming would:
1. Document this clearly as a precondition
2. Consider a debug assertion

This is a trust boundary issue - if the callback comes from untrusted code, this is a buffer overflow vector.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"me@mark.atwood.name","created_at":"2026-07-12T06:48:40.944763Z","created_by":"Mark Atwood","updated_at":"2026-07-12T06:48:40.944785Z"}

